Stade Brestois was officially born on June 26, 1950, from the merger of five local patronages: Armoricaine, Avenir, Milice Saint-Michel, Jeunes de Saint-Marc, and Flamme du Pilier Rouge.

Taking the place of Armoricaine de Brest, the club rapidly rose through the regional ranks, eventually reaching Division 2 in 1970 and achieving its first promotion to the top-flight Division 1 in 1979.

After a period of highs (including winning the Ligue 2 title in 1980–81) and subsequent lows that saw the club fall back into amateur championships in the 1990s, Stade Brestois began its revival. The club returned to the professional divisions in 2004 and has been a mainstay in French football since, culminating in a historic third-place finish in the 2023–24 Ligue 1 season, granting them their first-ever qualification for a European competition, the UEFA Champions League.
